<TITLE> Venezuela's Chavez seeks constitutional reforms </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 CARACAS, Aug 15 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez will present a package of constitutional reforms on Wednesday to end presidential term limits, curb central bank autonomy and consolidate his self-styled socialist revolution. The leftist former paratrooper, in open confrontation with the United States, has steadily increased his hold over the OPEC nation following a nationalization drive that pushed out two of the world's biggest energy companies. Chavez is scheduled to appear on Wednesday evening before the nation's Congress, which is 100 percent controlled by his supporters, to propose changes to the constitution he helped rewrite in 1999 after his landslide election a year earlier. "This reform is essential," Chavez said during a telephone interview with state television late on Tuesday. "We are starting a new era ... now heading straight toward socialism." While details of proposed reforms are still vague, Chavez has previously said he wants to lift a two-term limit on presidents and end the central bank's constitutional independence from the executive branch. Those proposals and his leftist politics have sparked the ire of critics and U.S. State Department officials who call him an authoritarian and accuse him of using Venezuela's oil wealth to threaten democracy in Latin America. Chavez is also expected to propose revamping local and municipal governments, which critics say would diminish the influence of mayors and governors -- the only posts where opposition politicians still have influence. Chavez has discussed other reforms, whose impact would not be immediately clear, such as creating "social property" as a counterpart to private property, and setting up a new "people's" branch of government. A close ally of Cuba's Fidel Castro, Chavez has used bountiful oil revenues to finance a broad network of social programs that have cultivated strong support among the poor, who overwhelmingly backed his 2006 reelection. This year, the Venezu